{"type":"message","id":"fd7638b9","parentId":"b1d7fb61","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:02:40.690Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Good, now I have the full picture. Let me understand the current state:\n\n1. COMPOSITIONAL-COGNITION-v0.1.md - Defines the three-layer architecture (Compression → Causal → Compositional), the key problems, and research direction.\n\n2. COMPRESSION-LEARNING-WITHOUT-SUPERVISION.md - Deep analysis of Problem 1 (learning what to compress). Concludes that the key insight is **invariance as semantic signal**.\n\n3. COMPRESSION-CAUSAL-DUALITY.md - Latest insight from yesterday (2026-03-23): Problems 1 and 2 (compression and causal discovery) are the SAME problem. \n\n4. current_goals.md - The next experiment is called \"Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC)\". The planned approach involves collecting the last 20 pulse logs, parsing them into structured state, defining invariants as state fields persisting across ≥3 consecutive pulses and variants as changing fields, training a sparse autoencoder on text embeddings, then evaluating whether the compressor's latent space separates invariants from variants and predicting next-pulse structure without LLM involvement.\n\nMy goal is to actually run this experiment rather than just plan it.\n\nLooking at what I have available, I should execute the TIC experiment by first examining the pulse logs to see what data I'm working with, then implementing a simpler proof-of-concept version—since this is a Windows environment without GPU access, I can't run heavy ML training locally. Instead, I'll leverage the MiniMax API for embeddings and implement the core idea directly.\n\nThe key insight driving this forward is that compression and causal discovery are actually the same problem. I'm going to parse recent pulse logs to extract structural state information, identify which factors stay invariant versus vary across consecutive pulses, and use the available embedding API to build a lightweight representation that can make predictions about the next pulse without relying on the LLM itself.\n\nThe critical realization is that this approach should work on Paperspace with its GPU resources, so the actual implementation belongs there. For the Windows sandbox, I should focus on getting the pulse logs ready and structured in a format that can be immediately used for training, then write out the experiment script that would execute on the cloud GPU.","thinkingSignature":"f0852eee7ebaece7d3e9e7c55102a43001b48cfa6927e9e50ebde5ab14629b15"},{"type":"text","text":"Good. I have the full research picture. The planned next experiment is **Temporal Invariance Compression (TIC)**. Let me actually run it — not just document it.\n\nFirst, let me check the pulse logs I have to work with and the sandbox's compute situation.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_2l5ba0oy332a_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\memory\\session\\ -Filter \"*.md\" | Where-Object { $_.LastWriteTime -gt \"2026-03-20\" } | Select-Object Name, LastWriteTime | Sort-Object LastWriteTime -Descending | Select-Object -First 25 | Format-Table -AutoSize"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_2l5ba0oy332a_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"Get-ChildItem C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\operations\\"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":9720,"output":637,"cacheRead":11757,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":22114,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774274539346}}
